text: Thats not a science fiction movie. Its actual real stuff. Only the story is fiction. But not the silence.  The Environmental Modification Convention (ENMOD), formally the Convention on the Prohibition of Military or Any Other Hostile Use of Environmental Modification Techniques is an international treaty prohibiting the military or other hostile use of environmental modification techniques having widespread, long-lasting or severe effects. It opened for signature on 18 May 1977 in Geneva and entered into force on 5 October 1978.  The Convention bans weather warfare, which is the use of weather modification techniques for the purposes of inducing damage or destruction. The Convention on Biological Diversity of 2010 would also ban some forms of weather modification or geoengineering.

text: Another natural disaster movie where you know the protagonist(s) will defy all statistically accurate life-or-death scenarios in actual world disasters.  We somehow saw the entire family in 2012 drive through an earthquake disaster, that conveniently chased them for plot purposes, and destroyed multiple other cars trying to escape. Why? Because protagonists love their plot armor. We also saw an amatuer pilot drive through a city of falling buildings at low altitudes and somehow didn't die there. Did I forget the part where Yellowstone erupted and the guy somehow managed to escape in the RV? Morale: If you have three lives, you are definitely dying in the three scenarios I just mentioned.  Let's not forget San Andreas when they couldn't even let the girl drown at the end. Nope, the whole family just had to live through boating in a flooded city, dodging collapsing buildings/debris, or basically any situation where water should've killed them.  Now this movie looks like it hired the special effects crew from Sharknado. Either that or Independance Day: Resurgence flippity-flopped at the box office and they couldn't afford an actual special effects team. Deus-Ex Machina, everybody!!!  - KingTurd

text: I hope this movie is fun. The visuals look a little unfinished at the moment, but I felt the comedy beats worked. It could have a great script and good performances to save it though. Music choice is outdated but so what. All in all, I predict th movie will do a bit of business, but this is no huge money maker or anything. It seems pretty standard in tone for a disaster blockbuster movie. Maybe one day we'll get something a little more serious and dramatic from this genre. It's very hard to do, because drama comes from characters and their struggles. But the struggle is so large scale in a film like this, I doubt we'll have any time for serious story telling, just a bunch of CGI effects so all the mongrels in the audience can clap and cheer. YAY! What a giant waist of money! CLAP! CHEER! great film.

text: I think a LOT of movies these days are made to be so excessively packed with insane action & graphics, it becomes a farce. Just like TV, which I gave up a few years ago, and now cannot fathom how so many people can STILL be glued to these idiot boxes, their attention spans being programmed into 10-20 second bites of info, anything more and they don't hear it!! THIS is why not enough people give AF about the "boring reality" of our politics, democracy, freedoms, and the oligarchy we now exist in! I have seen more and more movies with next to no plot that are entirely action & CGI, meant to keep your heart pounding, and what's funny is, they still weasel in brands & products into the best scenes, so your brain sucks it all up! I will probably still have to check out that Valerian flick, but it will be the first movie I've seen in a theater in over 6 months!
